====== String.prototype.trim() ======

This built-in function returns a String with leading and trailing whitespace removed.  Consider whitespace to be any of the following characters:

   * ''\u0009'' : Horizontal tab
   * ''\u000A'' : Line feed or New line
   * ''\u000B'' : Vertical tab
   * ''\u000C'' : Formfeed
   * ''\u000D'' : Carriage return
   * ''\u0020'' : Space
   * ''\u00A0'' : Non-breaking space
   * ''\u1680'' : Ogham space mark
   * ''\u180E'' : Mongolian vowel separator
   * ''\u2000'' : En quad
   * ''\u2001'' : Em quad
   * ''\u2002'' : En space
   * ''\u2003'' : Em space
   * ''\u2004'' : Three-per-em space
   * ''\u2005'' : Four-per-em space
   * ''\u2006'' : Six-per-em space
   * ''\u2007'' : Figure space
   * ''\u2008'' : Punctuation space
   * ''\u2009'' : Thin space
   * ''\u200A'' : Hair space
   * ''\u2028'' : Line separator
   * ''\u2029'' : Paragraph separator
   * ''\u202F'' : Narrow no-break space
   * ''\u205F'' : Medium mathematical space
   * ''\u3000'' : Ideographic space 

===== Comments =====

After [[http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.3/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#trim()|java.lang.String.trim]]

Do we perhaps want ''ltrim()''  and ''rtrim()'' in the style of Python's [[http://docs.python.org/lib/string-methods.html|lstrip()]] and [[http://docs.python.org/lib/string-methods.html|rstrip()]] , allowing user to just strip leading or trailing whitespace?

I also like how Python's [[http://docs.python.org/lib/string-methods.html|strip()]] method allows you to optionally specify which characters are to be stripped.

--- //[[iain.lamb@yahoo.com|Iain Lamb]] 2006/09/26 17:04//

The 3rd Edition considers space characters outside this range, including ''%%\u00A0%%'' and no less than 18 Unicode values outside the 0..255 range.  Is there any reason we should not strip those?

 --- //[[lth@opera.com|Lars T Hansen]] 2006/09/27 07:43//

FWIW, I just noticed that [[http://www.r6rs.org|the new Scheme report]] is specifying whitespace to be:
  * U+0009 (tab)
  * U+000A (linefeed)
  * U+000B (vtab)
  * U+000C (form feed)
  * U+000D (carriage return)
  * U+0020 (space)
  * anything in the [[http://www.fileformat.info/info/unicode/category/Zs/list.htm|Unicode category Zs]]
  * anything in the [[http://www.fileformat.info/info/unicode/category/Zl/list.htm|Unicode category Zl]]
  * anything in the [[http://www.fileformat.info/info/unicode/category/Zp/list.htm|Unicode category Zp]]

 --- //[[dherman@ccs.neu.edu|Dave Herman]] 2006/09/27 08:28//